result.execSummary:
The defendant Diana J. Kramarczyk was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Operate Firearm While Intoxicated, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 941.20(1)(b).
  • Possess Drug Paraphernalia, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.573(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Defendant may petition for early termination of probation term after completion of one year, provided request is joined by agent.

miscConds.notes:
Costs to be paid directly to the Waushara County Clerk of Court within 60 days or establish a payment plan.  Failure to pay may result in suspension of your driver's license, tax intercept, a civil judgment being entered against you, a warrant being issued for your arrest for contempt and/or the debt being turned over to a collection agency.

Attorney Fees in the amount of $639.04 to be paid directly to the Waushara Co Clerk of Court for Court Appointed Counsel.  Deposits previously paid in the amount of $300.000 have been applied.  The remaining balance of the Attorney Fees to be paid within 60 days or set up a payment plan with the Clerk.  Failure to comply will result in contempt procedures being initiated.

The defendant must maintain absolute sobriety, may not be present upon the premises of any bars (the restaurant or dining portion of the bar would not be considered a violation), and is prohibited from possessing/ingesting any impairing substances that have not been prescribed by a physician.  Defendant is prohibited from having any contact with the victim, unless as required through any Court proceeding.  Through verification brought to the Court's attention at the Plea and Sentencing Hearing, the Court ordered a firearm restriction due to a previous felony conviction in Winnebago Co back in 1981.
DNA sample to be provided and surcharge assessed.  Pursuant to s. 968.20, the Court orders forfeiture and destruction of the Ruger P-90 .45 caliber handgun.
